{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504937"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:23:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:23:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2390"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2390"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.08,0.2,0.03,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2390"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38407"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2390"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2390"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22867"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2960"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1536"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1565"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2538"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43137"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44352"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38407"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old woman presents with a two day history of fever, fatigue and joint pains. She presented with dysuria and urinary urgency seven days prior, was diagnosed with a urinary tract infection, and remains on a course of oral ciprofloxacin. Her urine culture showed E Coli sensitive to ciprofloxacin. Her history includes eczema. She takes ibuprofen as needed when she has a headache (approximately once per month) and has an implanon in situ.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 145/95 mmHg, pulse 75/min and temperature 38.1\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. She has a diffuse macular rash on her trunk. Her joint examination shows no active synovitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer urinalysis shows blood +, protein +, negative glucose, negative nitrites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer urine microscopy shows: RBC 9/hpf, WCC 17/hpf, and WCC casts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer blood results show: Cr 135 (90-120), Hb 117 (115-130), WCC 11 (2-11), and CRP 15.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discontinue ciprofloxacin","Initiate ceftriaxone","Initiate prednisolone","Initiate perindopril","Discontinue ibuprofen"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with fever, arthralgia, rash, haematuria and renal impairment, all of which is classical for \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Einterstitial nephritis (AIN)\u003C/strong\u003E. Her recent exposure to ciprofloxacin is relevant, as antibiotics commonly trigger AIN. AIN is a type IV hypersensitivity reaction that damages the kidney tubules and interstitium after exposure to a sensitising agent, often medications. The associated glomerulonephritis is a tubulointerstitial nephritis, with prominent interstitial infiltrate (with prominent eosinophils). There may be peripheral eosinophilia and urinary eosinophils can often be detected. Urinalysis typically reveals WCC casts. The management of AIN is \u003Cstrong\u003Ediscontinuation of the offending medication\u003C/strong\u003E (in this case, ciprofloxacin).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiating prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is not helpful in AIN. Prednisolone or other steroids are sometimes used in inflammatory glomerulonephritis, such as lupus nephritis. Currently, her urinalysis points to AIN over a glomerulonephritis. Her rash and joint exam are not consistent with a diagnosis of systemic lupus erythematosus, making lupus nephritis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiating ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E would be a possible option if a worsening urinary tract infection or ascending infection causing pyelonephritis was suspected. Pyelonephritis presents with fever and flank pain. However, this is less likely given she is on appropriate antimicrobial therapy for her urinary tract infection (confirmed by culture/sensitivity results), her CRP is relatively low, and her repeat urinalysis demonstrates negative nitrates.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiating perindopril\u003C/strong\u003E would be a potential option to treat her hypertension. Currently she does have an elevated blood pressure, however this is likely in the setting of her AIN. Her blood pressure is likely to improve as her AIN settles, given she does not have a history of hypertension. It would be unhelpful to treat her isolated high blood pressure immediately without addressing the underlying cause of the AIN.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscontinuing ibuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E is not really relevant because her use is so infrequent (she hasn\u0027t taken any for the past month). However, NSAIDs are nephrotoxic and in the setting of her acute kidney injury she should avoid ibuprofen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Fever, arthralgia, rash, haematuria and renal impairment are classical for acute interstitial nephritis","Acute interstitial nephritis is a type IV hypersensitivity reaction often triggered by medications"],"references":["Xu B, Murray M. Flucloxacillin induced acute renal failure. Aust Fam Physician. 2008 Dec;37(12):1009-11. PMID: 19142275.","Moledina D, Perazella M. Treatment of Drug-Induced Acute Tubulointerstitial Nephritis. Clinical Journal of the American Society of Nephrology. 2018;13(12):1785-1787."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22867"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2390"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/22867"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-07-26T14:07:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-02T17:53:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2390"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38407"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":